commentBody:
@Tex - Probably the best source for most available crosswords is the Daily Crossword Links email. If you use it to discover other crosswords, I bet you will find several that are more to your liking. 

Have fun!

<a href="https://dailycrosswordlinks.com/2025/02/22/saturday-february-22-2025" target="_blank">https://dailycrosswordlinks.com/2025/02/22/saturday-february-22-2025</a>/

@Tex 

You can always take a tip from Monty Python:  

"If you want to make it more difficult, try solving upside down with you head in a bucket of piranha fish."

@Megan 

I don't know, this GenXer knows GALENTINESDAY very well ever since Leslie Knope celebrated it on Parks and Rec. Many of my very non-teenaged friends use it on the regular. But I'm happy to hear current teens are also using it.  :-)  

Word History. Note: The coinage was apparently introduced on an episode of the television comedy series Parks and Recreation. The episode, entitled "Galentine's Day" and written by the show's co-creator Michael Schur, first aired on February 11, 2010.

@Marshall Walthew 
Here’s to Megan’s Gen-Alpha again!
🐍

@Francis 

Brilliant and unsettling.

That's really my sweet spot!! Thanks for noticing!!  😂

@Andrzej 

Yeah, my anchor there was deep in my childhood.  In the early days of television there was a show called "The Honeymooners".  Art Carney one of the four principles, and, to my mind, was more talented and funnier than Jackie Gleason, the star.

I hated the show, which I think I only saw in reruns.  But when you see a TV intro with the stars' names enough times, you'll remember them.

@nash.mark 

Yes, but I saw a you tube talking about that...but that sweet little wife gave as good as she got.

She wasn't afraid to stand up to him, and often did.  "I don't want to look at you.  I want to look at Liberace." when she was demanding a TV set.

@Steve 

Not true! A Burmese python typically grows to 16 feet, while a green anaconda often grows to 17 feet. 

But I share your pain. Giant before Great before Green added a minute or two to my solving time.

@Steve 

I guessing you're referring to the string length of "Burmese Python" and "Green Anaconda"?

I was trying to make something out of *something* constrictor, when Great Anaconda dawned on me.  Then a while latter until Green Anaconda insisted upon itself.

@Mike 
I wanted to add something oreganol, but I'm having trouble cumin up with anything.  Lack of caffeine is parsley to blame, no doubt.

Maybe some of the other sages will be able to garnish this bouquet.

@G @B

Thank you both so much!  

My problem with poetry is that I can rarely make it mean anything to myself.  I wish I could like it like some people do, but I just don't have the right kind of taste buds, I guess.

@Joseph 

I had a wall poster when I was a kid in the 80's which listed names for all sorts of groupings of animals, such as a "murder of crows". Gam of whales was the first in the list, and I've never forgotten it -- thankfully, since it shows up in crosswords! 

It may be that as a *marine biologist*, you're only looking at it from your area of expertise -- and "gam" may well be of a more literary persuasion. Perhaps an ornithologist can weigh in vis à vis "murder of crows" to add to the discussion!  :)

@Bob T.
DOH!
TX

@B 

Good points.  I had trouble with LOCS as well.  In fact, I just googled it and it's utterly new to me.

But the "lie" you mentioned--i took that as in falsehood.

@B 

Google "What is a protective hairstyle?"

I hadn't heard of nairas, but I got it from the crosses. The other things you mentioned just don't seem weird or obscure to me.

@Kate J 

"... without too much help from the crosses."

Ok, that shows me you're playing in an additional dimension from me.  I'm just glad I can get them *with* the help of the crosses.

@Andy 

I was fortunate to be in a Junior Year Abroad program in Paris, where one of the courses I took -- rather randomly -- was Greek & Roman Architecture. Taught completely in French. One of the few things I picked up in that class was about the three styles of Ancient Greek columns: Doric, Ionic and Corinthian. Who knew in what good stead that would hold me, between yesterday's crossword and today's!! I was able to fill in _O_IC, which helped a lot in that corner. 

That program included lots of amazing field trips, including to the impressive chateaux and the Da Vinci museum in the Loire Valley. Also Chartres cathedral and Giverny (Monet's house & gardens, gorgeous in spring), both of which are closer to Paris. Enjoy!!

@RM 

All those years later I still remember struggling with 6x7 and 7x8 for some reason... 

Math classes generally traumatized me. I was much more into humanities.

@Andrzej 

YES!!! Why those?  I bet if you asked 100 people which combinations gave them the most trouble, those two would be a a solid plurality.

If that's true, I'd love to know the reason.

@Francis,

A friend suggested staying in the moment to me when I was going through a difficult pending loss a number of years ago. At first I was annoyed by the suggestion, but then I found that it was the only way to have some kind of relief. I wasn’t haunted by what had gone on in the past, and not looking at a dismal future. It was surprisingly hard to do, but it helped. 

I also am sorry for your loss. Grief isn’t something you get over, you just learn to live with it, like a tree losing a limb and growing in a different direction, while keeping the scar. I’m sure Holly had a great life with you, as you did with her.

@Francis 
I love Schipperkes! Such mischievous little faces... 

I'm very sorry for your loss. 😟

@K 

If you're going to spoil the mini, at least you could do a Google search first. 

<a href="https://tofurky.com" target="_blank">https://tofurky.com</a>/

@Steve 
It has always been okay to discuss the mini here the same way the main puzzle is discussed. 
What should not be spoiled here are any of the other puzzles.

@Joseph 

😂

Yeah!  OMG the L's.  They're like zombies in a movie.  You think you've accounted for then all, then suddenly there's a new one.

@Ms. Billie M. Spaight 

Don't know where you are relative to me in stage of life, but sometime between when I was in secondary school and now, there were competitions in math ability.  

Would be similar to the Chess Team and the Debate Team, to some degree.

@Francis 

It's amazing how different American school is to ours. When I was in school in the 80s and 90s, we had none of the things that are staples across the pond, including [skill/activity] teams. We had classes, we were encouraged to engage in artistic shows at school, and there were regional and national competitons for the best students and athletes - I was among the winners of the national History Olympiad, for example.

Things may look different these days, but I have no kids and I'm not particularly interested in anybody's children so I wouldn't know.

@Barry Ancona 

WOW, that's a LOT of people good at maths! I'm impressed.

Also, it's one of those pictures I would never, ever see myself on :D

@Andrzej 

Now you've made me worry that you are already secretly embedded into one or both societies as a sleeper agent and this is all a clever ruse to avoid detection. 

<a href="https://youtu.be/vCsR6SHNY0M?si=hP0-AAc6R808ODOY" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/vCsR6SHNY0M?si=hP0-AAc6R808ODOY</a>

@HeathieJ

That clip pretty much illustrates my subertfuge abilities so don't worry :D

I visited the castle this scene was shot at BTW - there was an awsome audio guide recorded by Terry Jones. It covered both the castle's fascinating history and features (it is extremely well preserved from the medieval era), and its role in the Holy Grail movie. 

@Bob T. 

Thanks! I encountered this term in another NYT puzzle but it was good to be reminded of it not to forget it :)

@Margot (@jenesaiswha) as I wrote just above (or below depending on how you like to sort your comments):

I always thought of “reckoning” as more like approximating or estimating (or guesstimating), so not really something math team members (yes, I was one in HS) should be doing.

But looking up the definition, it can also refer to counting or calculating, so no complaints. I wanted the answer to be associated with orienteering or some other activity that requires one to approximate their location.

@Lewis 

Yes.  That suddenly flash when a group of scattered letters with several gaps suddenly becomes a whole word.

Magical is just the right word.

@Stuart S. I guess that was included to start this very dialogue. Our (Black or textured) hair is EXTREMELY dry. When we do all sorts of treatments that involve heat, it makes our hair very vulnerable to breakage. When we do styles like braids, locs, weaves, wigs many people not familiar with our hair attribute other reasons. In fact, we’re giving our hair a rest. 

For reference, my very white husband has the opposite problem. He has to wash his hair at least every other day or else it gets greasy. He applies no heat and never does anything protective (like sleep in a silk bonnet). Yet he fully “gets” all the steps I have to take.

I hope this clarifies a bit.

@Pani Korunova great answer!

Google had already given me the general idea - though the AI overview did not mention dreadlocks: “Examples of protective styles: Braids, twists, bantu knots, low buns, cornrows, wigs, and hair wraps”

While locs may be protective of the hair, it doesn’t seem like it would be a good idea for temporary protection. Isn’t it very difficult to undo that hairstyle without damage or hair loss?

@Pani Korunova 

It's wonderful, and more than I have reason to expect, when reading comments here expands my horizons so beautifully.

Thank you.

@Katie 

Haha... made me laugh.

That's one heck of a silver lining!

@Anne Jacko 

WRT xword puzzles, POD/GAM for a bunch of whales is like KEA/LOA following Mauna. You need a cross (or two) to know what to fill in.

IRL I would go with pod.

@Grant You're not wrong to date it that way, as the term GAM also refers to a social visit between whaling boats. 

A definition from ch 53 of Moby-Dick, titled 'The GAM': 

"GAM. Noun - A social meeting of two (or more) Whale-ships, generally on a cruising- ground; when, after exchanging hails, they exchange visits by boats' crews: the two captains remaining, for the time, on board of one ship, and the two chief mates on the other."

@Renegator 

Oh, phew! 

Thanks for clarifying, I'll go put my pearls away now!!  😆

@Grant 

While I cannot speak about locs from personal experience, I found some interesting info on Google. 

<a href="https://www.theloveofpeople.com/post/difference-between-locs-and-dreads" target="_blank">https://www.theloveofpeople.com/post/difference-between-locs-and-dreads</a>

@Robin 
I remember my 17 year old self going to see Harry and Tonto with my 18 year old boyfriend in a movie theater. I think he thought he was going to see a Honeymooners movie, but he did end up liking it, though he didn't understand why it made me cry. 
Anyway, it is too bad that it isn't available to be seen nowadays.

@Anna 

Congratulations! 

I'm certain you'll experience many more puzzle victories going forward!!  :-)

@Byron - BACH chose the notes for the compositions HE composed, but BACH was also an accomplished professional organist before he started composing music; he started while still a child. Many older members of his family were professional organists; it was sort of the family business. 

So, certainly he *chose* the notes for his own compositions, but when he played the works of others, the clue would certainly apply. 

I have no idea if the quotation is valid or misattributed, but it is certainly reasonable, considering he likely played many works composed by others.

@Endall I've been solving these puzzles online for about a year and find them getting easier and easier with time. I chalk it up to getting more familiar with the pop culture references and the commonly used filler clues/answers. If I go back in the archive 10, 20, 30 years, I find them impossible to solve (even some Mondays!). 

Either our brains are learning or the puzzles are easier. 
I did find today's puzzle (and a few recent Saturdays) to be surprisingly easy to solve in one sitting.

@Endall 

You might try the Saturday Stumper from Newsday (Long Island). 

Also, the Monday New Yorker is usually pretty tough, but maybe no harder than the Saturday NYT.

@Ellie 

We struggle mightily with the plurals of foreign words here.

One of the standard tricks is to put an S in the final block of any clue that suggests plural.  Causes all kinds of problems when the word comes from a language which doesn't pluralize like we do.

@Hugh 

I agree with Barry and will add that everyone solves according to their own capabilities, but when you get to the point where you can solve without looking anything up in any manner on any puzzle, you will have a much greater sense of satisfaction. 

And I’ll also say it’s great to be in southeast Mexico, where the Gulf still has its old name, and the temperatures are in the 80s.

@Hillary Rettig 

Sorry. It absolutely does. See sense 2, definition 2.  

<a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/gam" target="_blank">https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/gam</a>

@David Pearce I felt the same way partly due to too much of a sense of the word from shopping spree, but a spree ~= binge -> drinking bout. 
Locs, dreadlocks, protecting curly hair???
Never heard of that definition of GAM so didn't like crossing that with the neologism....
